postcontent:
Up for sale or trade is a Norinco Mak-90 chambered in 7.62x39. This is one of the best running AK variants that you will find on the market today. This ak has some marks and dings. It is a shooter. It has a small amount of very light surface blemishes from being carried, moved around in the safe, and taken out to shoot. It comes equipped with a tapco folding stock, tapco intrafuse handguards, and a saw style pistol grip. It also has a rail mount that has been welded on top of the dust cover. The barrel is threaded and this is the more desirable straight cut receiver. This gun is not perfect but it will serve you well for years to come. The bore is bright and shiny and the rifling is strong. If you have any questions, please feel free to email me. I will consider trades but cash is king. Trades must be extremely worth my while because my asking price is much less than what others are selling for. 


I also have up for sale or trade are three tactical Remington Shotguns. 

1. Remington 870 Tactical Magnum- 

This amazing shotgun was a limited run for the 2005 Shot Show. They are pretty difficult to find, especially at a fair price. It comes from the factory duracoated in OD green. The magazine tube capacity is 7+1 which is also a factory modification. This shotgun also has the pistol grip. There are a few light knicks and dings but nothing serious. The OD is actual OD green. I know it is difficult to see in the photos, but I assure you, it is OD green. I am asking $525 or best offer. 


2. Remington 870 Wingmaster- 

This 870 has been heavily upgraded and is in great condition. The finish has a bright color and really looks great with the stainless accents. The stock is a tapco intrafuse, molded pistol grip, a railed pump for mounting lights, etc.. It also comes with a forward grip mounted to the pump. When I purchased this shotgun, I changed the barrel to a mossberg brand 18.5 inch door breacher barrel. It also has a side shell holder. The magazine capacity is 4+1, so 8 shells are ready for your disposal. I am asking $400 or best offer.

3. Remington 870- 

This gun has been upgraded with a choate stock which also includes a 5 shell holder incorporated into the stock. The barrel is 18.5 inches long and is also a mossberg door breacher barrel which is a direct replacement for 870's. This gun is in good condition. I am asking $375 or best offer. 

I went on a tactical shotgun kick for quite a while but it is now time for me to move on. I will consider negotiating with a cash buyer that wants to purchase all three. If you have any questions, please feel free to email me. I am interested in some trades but cash is king, so the trade must be worth my while because I need cash more than anything.

title: For Trade:  HK USP Compact 9mm
location: Fort Lewis Area, Washington, United States
postcontent:
Up for trade is my HK USP Compact 9mm!!

The HK USP Compact is a small frame pistol capable of firing the most powerful cartridges in 9mm. Based on the full-size USP models, these handy pistols combine compact size with optimum effective shooting performance.

USP Compacts are smaller and lighter than large frame USPs. The reduction in trigger reach and grip circumference increases concealability and enhances shooting ergonomics. Unlike some subcompact semiautomatic pistols that use a difficult to shoot “two-finger grip” frame, the USP Compact uses a narrow, full-hand grip frame with a choice of interchangeable extended or flush-fitting magazine floorplates. This makes the pistol easy to shoot without sacrificing concealability.

All variants of the USP Compact have modified contoured slide and frame for effective concealability. Variants 1-7 also have a no snag, bobbed hammer. The extended slide release is contoured to reduce wear and tear on clothing when the pistol is carried concealed.

Using a modified linkless Browning-type action, the USP Compact is built to take the punishment of high energy +P and +P+ loads.

The USP Compact can also be converted from one type of trigger firing mode to another. This includes combination double-action and single-action modes and double action only modes. The USP Compact is currently available in four calibers and nine trigger / firing mode configurations, or virtually any firing mode imaginable.

To reduce the length of the slide and barrel on the USP Compact, the mechanical recoil reduction system found on large frame USPs has been replaced by a specially designed flat compression spring contained in the captive recoil spring assembly by a polymer absorber bushing. Service life is still engineered to exceed 20,000 rounds.

The frame mounted control lever, a combination safety and decocking lever, has a slimline profile for compactness but is still quickly accessible, unlike the slide mounted safeties common on many semiautomatic pistols.

Simple to maintain, the USP Compact is a reliable, safe, accurate, and highly concealable pistol with the performance of a full size handgun.

Comes with:

6 mags, Fobus Holster and Duel Mag Holster.

title: For Sale:  Pulsar N550
postcontent:
I have a Pulsar N550 digiscope for sale.  This is an interesting night/day scope with some interesting features.  Firstly, because it digitally enhances the image, there are no photosensitive films like with traditional night vision, meaning it can be used both day and night.  Additionally, because of its digital nature, it can be zeroed in with a single shot.  All you do is activate the one-shot-zero function, fire a round, keep the "x" on your point of aim and move the cross hair to the point of impact.  DONE!  It also has a build in IR light to illuminate your target on those extra dark nights!  Oh, and I almost forgot, it has a video out so that you can record everything your scope sees!  This is a really popular scope for nighttime hog hunts!  Has the nice carry bag, all cables and manual.  If you have any questions, feel free to ask.

I will consider trades, but I am really looking for a new patrol rifle.  I am looking for an LWRC M6A3 and would be willing to pony up cash if your trade is worth more than the scope (which an LWRC M6A3 would of course be, but I mean other trades), so if you have something else, let me know!

title: For Sale:  Rare 1925 Mosin Nagant Ex-Dragoon
postcontent:
I have a very nice rare 1925 Mosin Nagant Ex-Dragoon for sale. THIS IS NOT YOUR AVERAGE GUN SHOP VARIETY 91/30. It is a Izhevsk/Izhmash "Izzy" arsenal produced rifle. This is a Dragoon that was converted into a 91/30 in Russia when they had a surplus of Dragoons and switched over to making 91/30's. This has the hexagonal receiver, ALL numbers match including the receiver, bolt, magazine floor plate, and stock. The bore still has good rifling and it has NOT been counter bored. It is a very low original serial number - its serial number is just 386. What also makes this gun rare is the double striking of the Russian writing on the receiver. The top line was partially double struck in production. This rifle is also old enough that it doesn't have the standard "arrow inside a triangle" factory Izhevsk/Izhmash logo, it has the old style bow and arrow logo. There are several lines of Russian text on the receiver as well as the hammer and sickle emblem. This is a great addition to any collection. You will not find many others like this out there anywhere. Has original tool pouch, tools, cleaning rod, sling w/ Russian markings, oil bottle, bayonet and ammo pouch. I also have 20 rounds of ammunition to go with it.

Asking $180 obo. The only trades I would be interested in at this time would be for .22 pistols like a Browning Buckmark or S&W 22A.  Email if interested. Thanks for looking!

Hey guys, I have an almost new mossberg 935 12 gauge. I put less than 250 rounds through it and decided I could use something different. This is more of a hunting shotgun (ducks/turkey maybe?) and I'm not a hunter. I'm getting into skeet and trap so I think I'll get an over/under. I'll get a pump for home defense too.
Anyway, I've had it about a year now and only shot skeet with it once. I put a rail on the top which can be easily taken off. This shotgun is designed for 3" and 3.5" shells but I have been able to get the 2 3/4" to cycle. From what I've read, once you get done with the break in period the 2 3/4 shells will cycle just fine. Just note I'm not out of the break-in round count yet.
